title: Fuse attention for BERT without num_heads, hidden_size
body:
**Description**: 

Currently, when user specifies a wrong hidden_size, the optimizer will not fuse attention silently (there is debug log but not show by default). Update the handling to be more user friendly.

(1) Update attention fusion for BERT model to pass without user specified num_heads or hidden_size. If user specified wrong value, the tool will print warnings but still fuse the Attention node. Add a test case for this.
(2) Update the default value of num_heads and hidden_size to be 0. That's consistent with the default values in API. In this way, user need not specify these parameters for BERT model.
(3) Do not show same warning multiple times.
(4) Update help description for optimizer arguments.

**Motivation and Context**

title: Expose an API to query the CUDA compute stream to launch a custom kernel
body:
**Description**: 

Description as title.

- Particularly useful for the scenario where-in custom ops compiled into shared libraries need to achieve implicit synchronization with ORT's CUDA kernels
    -  Also useful for the "regular" custom ops scenario where custom ops are not compiled into a shared library and directly registered used the APIs. But that had a work-around of creating a session with a user-created stream and just using that stream to launch custom kernels. This work-around is much harder to achieve when custom ops are compiled into shared libraries (See https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/6971)

- Currently, we only have one compute stream per-session. So, this could be a session level API. But it is kept as an API at the `OrtKernelContext`  level to keep the design flexible enough for the case where-in (in future) sessions could have multiple streams (one per host thread).  When the sessions starts maintaining one stream per host thread, the API will start returning the stream corresponding to that thread.  

**Motivation and Context**
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/7068#discussion_r602245891

title: Dropout Vectorized Kernel
body:
**Description**: CUDA summary analysis for ULR-XL model shows room to improve performance in areas of dropout, biasdropout, and dropoutgrad CUDA kernels. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4484531/134406350-6fe18810-1b72-4851-93ad-c5d3a26f2ee5.png)

With some investigation, we experiment it with vectorized data load/store approach in CUDA kernel, and the results shows ~0.75% of perf gain comparing to the original non-vectorized kernel logic in a short test (3k steps w/ full recipe on ITP cluster).

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4484531/134405852-896e93dc-40c7-4e33-85e5-a5aca867dd74.png)

Another test with nvprof profiler also show consistent observation on a local run for 10 steps:

title: Add  Transpose, Reshape, Pow and  LeakyRelu ops to DNNL  execution provider
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
This adds 4 additional operators to the DNNL execution provider
- Transpose
- Reshape
- Pow
- LeakyRelu

In addition to the Operators, this also contains two code improvement commits. 
One commit updates the dnnl_code_capability code to use enums instead of strings.
The other commit updates the DnnlSubgraphPrimitve.GetMemory function to more closely resemble the other member functions making the code more straightforward to use. 

Both of these changes really only affect the DNNL execution provider code and will not affect other execution providers.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
This increases the Operators supported by the DNNL execution provider.

title: UWP Apps are broken in 1.9 due to Store compliant builds referencing LoadPackagedLibrary
body:
UWP Apps are broken in 1.9 due to Store compliant builds referencing LoadPackagedLibrary

Issue: This change (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/8753) forced the Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning WinRT Store builds to use LoadPackagedLibrary for StoreApps to make the binaries compliant with Store WACK Policies (this is now not needed). Because of this change all load library calls from inside the binaries were swapped to use LoadPackagedLibrary. However, LoadPackagedLibrary cannot find system32 dlls like combase, and other winrt types, and fails.

Fix: For UWP Store binaries use the statically linked desktop binaries. The desktop binaries are now compliant with Store WACK policies, as WACK certification from the latest Windows SDKs do not require Store only apis.

title: legacy_megatron-lm/deepspeed_ZERO1&2 FP16_Optimizer wrapper
body:
**Description**: FP16_Optimizer wrapper.

## How to Use: ##

Usage:
```
        1. DeepSpeed ZeRO Optimizer Override
            from onnxruntime.training.optim.fp16_optimizer import FP16_Optimizer
            optimizer = Adam(param_groups,
                             lr=args.lr,
                             weight_decay=args.weight_decay,
                             betas=(args.adam_beta1, args.adam_beta2),
                             eps=args.adam_eps)
            model, optimizer, _, lr_scheduler = deepspeed.initialize(
                model=model,
                optimizer=optimizer,
                args=args,
                lr_scheduler=lr_scheduler,
                mpu=mpu,
                dist_init_required=False)
            if args.fp16:
                optimizer = FP16_Optimizer(optimizer)

        2. Megatron-LM-v1.1.5 Optimizer Override:
            from onnxruntime.training.optim.fp16_optimizer import FP16_Optimizer as ORT_FP16_Optimizer
            optimizer = Adam(param_groups,
                             lr=args.lr,
                             weight_decay=args.weight_decay,
                             betas=(args.adam_beta1, args.adam_beta2),
                             eps=args.adam_eps)
            # Wrap into fp16 optimizer.
            if args.fp16:
                optimizer = FP16_Optimizer(optimizer,
                                           static_loss_scale=args.loss_scale,
                                           dynamic_loss_scale=args.dynamic_loss_scale,
                                           dynamic_loss_args={
                                                'scale_window': args.loss_scale_window,
                                                'min_scale': args.min_scale,
                                                'delayed_shift': args.hysteresis},
                                           verbose=True)
                optimizer = ORT_FP16_Optimizer(optimizer,
                                               get_tensor_model_parallel_rank=mpu.get_model_parallel_rank,
                                               get_tensor_model_parallel_group=mpu.get_model_parallel_group)



```

## More Details ##

It is found, some version of APEX's FP16_Optimizer and DeepSpeed Optimizers 
1). are using serial overflow check, which introduces many GPU->CPU copy. 
2). are using serial gradient norm calculation, also having many GPU->CPU copy. 

Both can be addressed by simple calls, either into Torch, or Apex. This could significant decrease the latency of check overflow and clip gradient norm.  

### 24 layer of GPT2 Megatron-LM model, 

Without this change:

     iteration       98/     100 | elapsed time per iteration (ms): 186.1 | learning rate: 3.891E-06 | lm loss: 9.072313E+00 | loss scale: 262144.0 | number of skipped iterations:   0 | number of nan iterations:   0 |
    time (ms) | forward: 57.49 | backward: 119.91 | backward-backward: 59.34 | backward-allreduce: 11.33 | backward-master-grad: 30.21 | backward-clip-grad: 18.30 | optimizer: 6.96 | batch generator: 1.37
     iteration       99/     100 | elapsed time per iteration (ms): 192.1 | learning rate: 3.937E-06 | lm loss: 9.137538E+00 | loss scale: 262144.0 | number of skipped iterations:   0 | number of nan iterations:   0 |
    time (ms) | forward: 59.64 | backward: 123.78 | backward-backward: 59.00 | backward-allreduce: 13.23 | backward-master-grad: 32.41 | backward-clip-grad: 18.44 | optimizer: 6.94 | batch generator: 1.38

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/134792716-a88efdfd-aa20-4022-b6e1-42ef9e70f995.png)

With this change:

    iteration       98/     100 | elapsed time per iteration (ms): 144.2 | learning rate: 3.891E-06 | lm loss: 9.183796E+00 | loss scale: 262144.0 | number of skipped iterations:   0 | number of nan iterations:   0 |
    time (ms) | forward: 56.70 | backward: 79.34 | backward-backward: 58.12 | backward-allreduce: 11.99 | backward-master-grad: 5.98 | backward-clip-grad: 2.72 | optimizer: 6.88 | batch generator: 1.05
    iteration       99/     100 | elapsed time per iteration (ms): 149.7 | learning rate: 3.937E-06 | lm loss: 9.250105E+00 | loss scale: 262144.0 | number of skipped iterations:   0 | number of nan iterations:   0 |
    time (ms) | forward: 56.72 | backward: 84.77 | backward-backward: 58.31 | backward-allreduce: 14.76 | backward-master-grad: 5.99 | backward-clip-grad: 5.09 | optimizer: 6.95 | batch generator: 1.16

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/134792729-71b8b1d2-035f-4287-bb3e-c389c59a24c2.png)

elapsed time per iteration dropped ~22.38%, optimizer checkoverflow+clipgradnorm takes from 52ms to 10.8ms, reducing 79% of its overhead.


Usage:
```
    from onnxruntime.training.ortmodule.experimental.optimizer import FP16_Optimizer as ORT_FP16_Optimizer
    optimizer = Adam(param_groups,
                         lr=args.lr,
                         weight_decay=args.weight_decay,
                         betas=(args.adam_beta1, args.adam_beta2),
                         eps=args.adam_eps)

    # Wrap into fp16 optimizer.
    if args.fp16:
        optimizer = FP16_Optimizer(optimizer,
                                   static_loss_scale=args.loss_scale,
                                   dynamic_loss_scale=args.dynamic_loss_scale,
                                   dynamic_loss_args={
                                       'scale_window': args.loss_scale_window,
                                       'min_scale': args.min_scale,
                                       'delayed_shift': args.hysteresis},
                                    verbose=True)
        optimizer = ORT_FP16_Optimizer(optimizer, get_tensor_model_parallel_rank=mpu.get_model_parallel_rank, 
                                       get_tensor_model_parallel_group=mpu.get_model_parallel_group)

```

### DeepSpeed ZeRO Optimizer

Without the change, optimizer takes 25ms, out of 170ms for the each iteration latency.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/135267690-0f377291-0d4f-4f90-a93c-c5f3c538d37b.png)

With this change, optimizer takes 9ms. 15.597ms our of previous 170ms is saved, 9.17% is saved.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/135267943-b52f4b75-1a6a-4cf9-aab8-9fbccb1c5894.png)


Usage

        from onnxruntime.training.ortmodule.experimental.optimizer import FP16_Optimizer as ORT_FP16_Optimizer
        model, optimizer, _, lr_scheduler = deepspeed.initialize(
            model=model,
            optimizer=optimizer,
            args=args,
            lr_scheduler=lr_scheduler,
            mpu=mpu,
            dist_init_required=False)

        if args.fp16 and args.use_ort_opt:
            optimizer = ORT_FP16_Optimizer(optimizer)

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Optimize Variadic Elementwise Ops
body:
Optimize varadic elementwise Ops in two cases:
- if all inputs are same size, use NoBroadcastBatchImplDispatchTarget kernel sequentially to take (at most) 8 inputs each time to handle all inputs.
- If there is one input has same size as output, remove the memset and 1st Add for GeneralImplDispatchTarget kernel.

Use Sum op to sum 12 [4096, 4096] tensors as test case:
- Before the change, there are one memset (76us) and 12 Add (~240us each), total time is 3ms
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11661208/134795651-6e0d9e9c-afad-42c4-b958-9ba02e77222a.png)

- After the change, there are VariadicElementWiseNoBroadcastInputBatchKernel<8> (830us) and VariadicElementWiseNoBroadcastInputBatchKernel<5> (540us), total time is 1.4ms
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11661208/134795679-c287a8a9-abcb-4488-b150-5eec8f78daf9.png)

title: Add same_shape case for BiasDropout
body:
**Description**: Add same_shape case for BiasDropout

**Motivation and Context**
Currently `BiasDropout` requires bias to be a 1-D tensor, this PR adds a new case where bias has the same shape as the data.
This is helpful for Nvidia Megatron-LM model, https://github.com/NVIDIA/Megatron-LM/blob/3860e995269df61d234ed910d4756e104e1ab844/megatron/model/transformer.py#L471

In Megatron-LM GPT-2 model, some perf gains are obtained:
Before: Add + Dropout + Add, 120.632 s/layer * 24 layers, 44.259 ms (forward) + 52.696 ms (backward)
After: BiasDropout, 75.8 s/layer * 24 layers, 43.316 ms (forward) + 52.226 (backward)

kernel saving: (120.632 - 75.8) s * 24 = 1076 s
real time saving for fw+bw: 1.46 %

title: Decouple GraphExecutionManager and accept extra exporter options
body:
Current ORTModule class has a TorchModuleInterface which was meant to wrap PyTorch API's only. However, TorchModuleInterface also defines and store GraphExecutionManager, which is responsible for executing ONNX graphs using ORT.

This PR moves GraphExecutionManager from within TorchModuleInterface to ORTModule, which is the main class and responsible for orchestrating the graph. It also allows extra exporter arguments to be specified using internal APIs.

The main benefit of such change is easier ORTModule extensions, as the new version has a lower coupling and higher cohesion.

Currently ORTModule is packed with 3 torch c++ extensions and it doesn't support additional extensions without code change.
However, torch c++ extensions are an important means to allow users to add C++ code into ORTModule

A future PR can make the copy to ortmodule package optional

title: Allow ORTModule custom exporter params + training mode fix
body:
Currently ORTModule does not allow users to change how models are exported. This PR allows users to extend ORTModule and add *new* arguments to the torch exporter. Parameters that are already specified by ORTModule cannot be overriden

ORTModule also assumes user model is in training mode, which can cause an mismatch when the initial state of training mode is False. This PR adds a check to sync internal state of training mode with user model's

title: [js/web] Support opset-13 for squeeze, unsqueeze, maxpool, pad, cast and clip
body:
It supports opset-13 for certain kernels, such as squeeze, unsqueeze, pad, cast, and clip. It supports maxpool, but it only allows input changes from attributes to inputs and doesn't correctly handle storage order and ceil mode yet.

It enables opset-13 model test and changes test data set accordingly.

title: Remove usage of wstring_convert
body: **Description**: One customer recently reported that wstring_convert crashes on Windows in VTL1 mode because it calls APIs unavailable there. Also, we removed all uses of wstring_convert from WinML and ORT in the past because, due to what seems like poor implementation on the Microsoft STL, referencing wstring_convert in Windows adds 400KB of conversion code to the binary, including some locale and currency conversion code (even in Release mode with LTO), adding a lot of code that never gets called. In Windows we try to call the Windows API rather than go through the STL.

Fix: Force Windows AI NuGet pipelines onto 19041.
